<subsection xml:id="subsec-SingleMeanHurricanes">
  <title>Hurricane Hypothesis Tests</title>
<p> The data in <em>Hurricanes</em> contains the number of hurricanes that made landfall on the eastern coast of the United States from 1914 to 2022. Suppose we are interested in comparing the mean number of hurricanes that make landfall during different time periods. <em> Early Years </em> consists of the number of hurricanes from 1914 to 1933 and <em>Later Years </em> consists of the number of hurricanes from 2003 to 2022.</p>
<p> In StatKey under <term>One Quantitative Variable</term>, <c>Upload </c>the data file and select each variable to find the summary statistics. Click on <c>Change Column</c> to change variable names. </p>

<exercise> <title> summary statistics </title>
  <statement>
    <p>Find the sample size, mean, and standard deviation for <em> Hurricanes</em>, <em>Early Years</em> and <em> Later Years.</em> Round to two decimal places. </p>
  </statement>
 <solution> 
  <p> The Hurricanes data lists 109 hurricanes with a mean = 5.872, standard deviation = 2.752, with values ranging from 0 to 15 hurricanes within a year. </p>
  <p> The Early Years is a ample of 20 hurricanes with a mean = 4.3 and standard deviation 2.774 with values ranging from 0 to 11 hurricanes. </p>
  <p> The Later Years is a ample of 20 hurricanes with a mean = 7.75 and standard deviation 3.338 with values ranging from 2 to 15 hurricanes. </p>
</solution>
</exercise> 
<p> We are going to investigate if the mean number of hurricanes in the Early Years is significantly less than the mean of 5.8 hurricanes per year.</p>

<exercise> <title> hypotheses </title> 
  <statement>
  <p> We are going to investigate if the mean in Early Years is significantly less than the mean of 5.8 hurricanes per year. What are the null and alternative hypotheses? </p>
  </statement>
<solution> <p> <m> Ho: \mu =5.8</m> and <m>Ha: \mu \lt 5.8 </m> </p> 
</solution>
</exercise> 
<exercise> <title> Statistical Test </title> 
  <statement>
    <p> What is the statistical test value? </p>
  </statement>
<solution> <p> <m> T= \frac{4.3-5.8} {\frac{2.77} {\sqrt{20}}}= -2.42</m> </p> 
</solution>
</exercise> 
<exercise> <title> p-value </title> 
  <statement>
    <p> Find the p-value for the  statistical test value </p>
  </statement>
<solution> <p> p-value=0.013 with 19 df for left tail test </p>
</solution>
</exercise> 
<exercise> <title> decision </title> 
  <statement>
    <p> Based the p-value, should your reject or not reject the null hypothesis?</p>
  </statement>
<solution> <p> since p-value 0.013 is less than alpha (.05), we should reject Ho </p>
</solution>
</exercise> 
<exercise> <title> conclusion </title> 
  <statement>
    <p> What is the conclusion?  </p>
  </statement>
<solution> <p> Conclude the mean in Early Years hurricanes is significantly less than the mean of 5.8 hurricanes per year.</p>
</solution>
</exercise> 

<p> We are going to investigate if the mean number of hurricanes in the Later Years is significantly more than the mean of 5.8 hurricanes per year. </p> 
<exercise> <title> hypotheses </title> 
  <statement>
    <p> We are going to investigate if the mean in Later Years is significantly more than the mean of 5.8 hurricanes per year. What are the null and alternative hypotheses? </p>
  </statement>
<solution> <p> <m> Ho: \mu =5.8</m> and <m>Ha: \mu \gt 5.8 </m> </p> 
</solution>
</exercise> 
<exercise> <title> test value </title> 
  <statement>
    <p> What is the statistical test value? </p>
  </statement>
<solution> <p> <m> T= \frac{7.75-5.8} {\frac{3.34} {\sqrt{20}}}= 2.61
</m> </p> 
</solution>
</exercise> 
<exercise> <title> p-value </title> 
  <statement>
   <p> Find the p-value for the  statistical test value </p>
  </statement>
<solution> <p> p-value=0.0086 with 19 df  for a right tail test </p>
</solution>
</exercise> 
<exercise> <title> decision </title> 
  <statement>
    <p> Based the p-value, should your reject or not reject the null hypothesis?</p>
  </statement>
<solution> <p> since p-value 0.0086 is less than alpha (.05), we should reject Ho </p>
</solution>
</exercise> 
<exercise> <title> conclusion </title> 
  <statement>
   <p> What is the conclusion?  </p>
  </statement>
<solution> <p> Conclude the mean in Later Years hurricanes is significantly more than the mean of 5.8 hurricanes per year.</p>
</solution>
</exercise> 

</subsection>

<subsection xml:id="subsec-SingleMeanTestPractice">
  <title>Practice Problems</title>

 
<exercise xml:id="oceanpH-hypothesis-test">
  <title> Change in Ocean pH</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Scientists have long used a historical average surface ocean pH of about
      <m>8.20</m> as a benchmark. Recent National Ocean and Atmospheric Administration (NOAA) summaries report that global surface
      ocean pH has decreased by about <m>0.1</m> to <m>0.11</m> units since the
      Industrial Revolution, suggesting modern ocean pH may now be lower on average.
    </p>
    <p>
      A marine science team collects a random sample of <m>16</m> recent surface-ocean
      pH measurements from one region and obtains a sample mean of
      <m>\bar{x}=8.08</m> and a sample standard deviation of <m>s=0.12</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      At the <m>0.05</m> significance level, test whether the true mean ocean pH
      in this region has changed from the historical value of <m>8.20</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      State the null and alternative hypotheses, compute the test statistic,
      estimate the <term>p-value</term>, and state a conclusion in context.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <hint>
    <p>
      Because the population standard deviation is unknown, use a one-sample
      <m>t</m>-test for the mean.
    </p>
    <p>
      For the question of whether the pH has <q>changed</q>, use a two-sided test:
    </p>
    <p> <m>H_0:\mu=8.20 \qquad H_a: \mu\ne 8.20 </m> </p>
    <p>
      Then compute
    </p>
    <p> <md>t=\frac{\bar{x}-\mu_0}{s/\sqrt{n}}.</md> </p>
  </hint>
  <answer>
    <p> The hypotheses are <m>H_0:\mu=8.20</m> and <m>H_a: \mu \ne 8.20</m>.
      The test statistic is <m>t=-3.88</m> with <m>df=15</m>.
      The two-sided <term>p-value</term> is <m>0.0017</m>.
      Since the <em>p-value</em> is less than 0.05, we reject <m>H_0</m>.
      Conclude there is significant evidence that the mean ocean pH in this region has changed from 8.    </p>
  </answer>
  <solution>
    <p> We test whether the population mean pH differs from the historical benchmark
      of <m>8.20</m>.     </p>
    <p> The hypotheses are    
    <m> H_0:\mu=8.20 \qquad H_a:\mu\ne 8.20.</m> </p>
    <p> Because the population standard deviation is unknown and the sample size is
      16, we use a one-sample <m>t</m>-test.    </p>
    <p> The standard error is     
    <md>\frac{s}{\sqrt{n}}=\frac{0.12}{\sqrt{16}}=\frac{0.12}{4}=0.03.</md> </p>
    <p> The test statistic is     </p>
    <p> <md>t=\frac{8.08-8.20}{0.03}=\frac{-0.12}{0.03}=-4.00.</md> </p>
    <p> The degrees of freedom are <m>df=16-1=15.</m> </p>
    <p> A test statistic of <m>t=-3.89</m> with <m>15</m> degrees of freedom gives a two-sided <term>p-value</term> <m>=2(.0018)=.0036</m>.     </p>
    <p> Since the <term>p-value</term> is less than the significance level
      <m>\alpha=0.05</m>, we reject the null hypothesis.     </p>
    <p>
      There is sufficient statistical evidence to conclude that the true mean
      ocean pH in this region has changed from the historical value of <m>8.20</m>.
      Because the sample mean is lower than <m>8.20</m>, the data suggests the change
      is a decrease in pH level.
    </p>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="oceanDecph-hypothesis-test">
  <title> Decreasing in Ocean pH</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Scientists have historically used an average surface ocean pH of about
      <m>8.20</m> as a benchmark. Recent NOAA summaries indicate that average
      surface ocean pH has decreased over time, motivating a test of whether
      the mean pH in a particular region is now lower than <m>8.20</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      A marine science team collects a random sample of <m>12</m> recent
      surface-ocean pH measurements from one coastal region:
    </p>
    <p>
      <m>8.07,\; 8.12,\; 8.05,\; 8.10,\; 8.09,\; 8.03,\; 8.11,\; 8.06,\; 8.08,\; 8.04,\; 8.13,\; 8.07</m>
    </p>
    <p>
      At the <m>0.05</m> significance level, test whether the true mean ocean pH
      in this region has decreased from the historical value of <m>8.20</m>.
    </p>
    <p> State the null and alternative hypotheses, compute the test statistic,
      estimate the <em>p-value</em>, and state a conclusion in context.    </p>
  </statement>
  <hint>
    <p> Use a one-sample <m>t</m>-test for a population mean, since the population
      standard deviation is unknown.     </p>
    <p>  For a one-sided test of decrease, use     </p>
    <p> <md>H_0: \mu=8.20 \qquad H_a: \mu \lt 8.20.</md> </p>
    <p> Then compute the sample mean, sample standard deviation, and test statistic  </p>
    <p> <md>t=\frac{\bar{x}-\mu_0}{s/\sqrt{n}}.</md> </p>
  </hint>
  <answer>
    <p>
      The hypotheses are <m>H_0:\mu=8.20</m> and <m>H_a: \mu \lt 8.20</m>.
      From the data, <m>\bar{x}\approx 8.079</m> and <m>s \approx 0.033</m>.
      The test statistic is <m>t\approx -12.59</m> with
      <m>df=11</m>. The <em>p-value</em> is effectively <m>0</m>
      (far less than <m>0.05</m>), so we reject <m>H_0</m>.
      There is strong evidence that the true mean ocean pH in this region
      has decreased below <m>8.20</m>.
    </p>
  </answer>
  <solution>
    <p> We want to test whether the population mean ocean pH is lower than
      the historical benchmark of <m>8.20</m>.     </p>
    <p> The hypotheses are     
    <md> H_0:\mu=8.20 \qquad H_a:\mu \lt 8.20     </md> </p>
    <p>       Because the population standard deviation is unknown, we use a one-sample
      <m>t</m>-test for the mean.     </p>
    <p>  First compute the sample statistics from the data:    </p>
    <p> <md>\bar{x}=\frac{8.07+8.12+8.05+8.10+8.09+8.03+8.11+8.06+8.08+8.04+8.13+8.07}{12}\approx 8.079.</md> </p>
    <p> <md>s\approx 0.033.</md> </p>
    <p>       The sample size is <m>n=12</m>, so the degrees of freedom are  <m>df=12-1=11.</m> </p>
    <p> The standard error is     
    <md>\frac{s}{\sqrt{n}} \approx \frac{0.033}{\sqrt{12}} \approx 0.0095.</md> </p>
    <p>       The test statistic is     
    <md>t=\frac{\bar{x}-\mu_0}{s/\sqrt{n}}=\frac{8.079-8.20}{0.0095}\approx -12.77.</md> </p>
    <p>
      With <m>df=11</m>, this gives a one-sided <term>p-value</term> that is
      extremely small, far below <m>0.05</m>.
    </p>
    <p>       Therefore, we reject <m>H_0</m>.     </p>
    <p>       There is strong statistical evidence that the true mean ocean pH in this
      region has decreased below <m>8.20</m>.     </p>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="ex-one-mean-ocean-salinity">
<title> Ocean Salinity</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      The average salinity of ocean water is often taken to be about
      35 practical salinity units (psu). A group of marine scientists
      wants to know whether the mean salinity of surface water near the polar
      oceans is lower than 35 psu, possibly because of melting sea ice
      and freshwater input.
    </p>
    <p>
      A random sample of <m>10</m> salinity measurements is taken from surface
      waters near the poles, with the following results:
    </p>
    <table>
      <title>Surface Ocean Salinity Near the Poles (psu)</title>
      <tabular>
        <row>
          <cell>34.7</cell>
          <cell>34.8</cell>
          <cell>34.6</cell>
          <cell>34.9</cell>
          <cell>34.5</cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell>34.7</cell>
          <cell>34.8</cell>
          <cell>34.6</cell>
          <cell>34.7</cell>
          <cell>34.9</cell>
        </row>
      </tabular>
    </table>
    <p>
      At the <m>\alpha =0.05</m> significance level, test whether the mean salinity of
      surface water near the poles is less than 35 psu.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution> <title> Hypotheses</title>
    <p>
      This is a one-sample <m>t</m>-test for a population mean.
    </p>
    <p>
      Let <m>\mu</m> be the true mean salinity of surface water near the poles.
      The hypotheses are
      <m>H_0:\mu=35</m>
      and
      <m>H_a:\mu \lt 35</m>.
    </p>
  </solution>
  <solution> <title> Statistical Test</title>
    <p>
      For the sample, the sample mean is
      <m>\bar{x}=34.72</m> psu,  the sample standard deviation is  <m>s\approx 0.132</m> psu, and the sample size is  <m>n=10</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      The test statistic is
      <md>
        t=\frac{\bar{x}-\mu_0}{s/\sqrt{n}} =\frac{34.72-35}{0.132/\sqrt{10}}   \approx -6.71.
      </md>
    </p>
</solution>
  <solution> <title> p-value</title>
    <p>
      The degrees of freedom are <m>df=n-1=9</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      Using a <m>t</m>-distribution with <m>9</m> degrees of freedom, the
      <m>p</m>-value is less than <m>0.0001</m>. StatKey gives <m>p=.000047</m>
    </p>
  </solution>
  <solution> <title> Conclusion</title>
    <p>
      Since <m>p \lt 0.05</m>, we reject <m>H_0</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      There is sufficient evidence at the <m>0.05</m> significance level to
      conclude that the mean salinity of surface water near the poles is less
      than <m>35</m> psu.
    </p>
    <p>
      In context, these data support the idea that polar surface waters are less
      salty than the typical average ocean salinity.
    </p>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="ex-one-mean-audiology">
<title>Hearing</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      An audiologist wants to determine whether the mean hearing threshold at
      1000 Hz for a group of adults differs from the standard reference level of 20 decibels (dB). A random sample of 10 adults is  selected, and each person's hearing threshold at 1000 Hz is  measured.
    </p>
    <table>
      <title>Hearing Thresholds at 1000 Hz (dB)</title>
      <tabular>
        <row>
          <cell>22</cell>
          <cell>19</cell>
          <cell>24</cell>
          <cell>21</cell>
          <cell>23</cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell>20</cell>
          <cell>25</cell>
          <cell>18</cell>
          <cell>22</cell>
          <cell>24</cell>
        </row>
      </tabular>
    </table>
    <p>
      At the <m>0.05</m> significance level, test whether the mean hearing
      threshold differs from <m>20</m> dB.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution> <title> Hypotheses</title>
    <p>
      This is a one-sample <m>t</m>-test for a population mean.
    </p>
    <p>
      Let <m>\mu</m> be the true mean hearing threshold at 1000 Hz. The
      hypotheses are
      <md>H_0:\mu=20</md>
      <md>H_a:\mu \neq 20</md>.
    </p>
  </solution>
  <solution> <title> Statistical Test</title>
    <p>
      For the sample, the sample size is <m>n=10</m>, the sample mean is
      <m>\bar{x}=21.8</m>, and the sample standard deviation is
      <m>s\approx 2.30</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      The test statistic is
      <md>
        t=\frac{\bar{x}-\mu_0}{s/\sqrt{n}}
        =\frac{21.8-20}{2.30/\sqrt{10}}     \approx 2.47.
      </md>
    </p>
</solution>
  <solution> <title> p-value</title>
    <p>   The degrees of freedom are  <m>df=n-1=9</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      Using a <m>t</m>-distribution with <m>9</m> degrees of freedom, the two-tailed test gives   <m>p =2(0.018)=0.036</m>.
    </p>
  </solution> 
  <solution> <title> Conclusion</title>
    <p>
      Since <m>p \lt 0.05</m>, we reject <m>H_0</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      There is sufficient evidence at the 0.05 significance level to
      conclude that the mean hearing threshold at 1000 Hz differs from 20 dB.
    </p>
    <p>
      Because the sample mean is greater than 20 dB, the data suggest
      that this group has a higher average hearing threshold than the standard
      reference level.
    </p>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="ex-one-mean-carbon-dioxide-ocean">
<title> Coastal Carbon Dioxide</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Oceanographers are studying the amount of dissolved carbon dioxide in a
      coastal region of the ocean. Historical records indicate that the mean
      dissolved carbon dioxide concentration in this region is 2.10 millimoles per liter. A researcher wants to determine whether the current mean dissolved carbon dioxide concentration differs from this historical value.
    </p>
    <p>
      A random sample of <m>12</m> water measurements is collected, with the
      following dissolved carbon dioxide concentrations, in millimoles per liter:
    </p>
    <table>
      <title>Dissolved Carbon Dioxide Concentrations (mmol/L)</title>
      <tabular>
        <row>
          <cell>2.18</cell>
          <cell>2.24</cell>
          <cell>2.09</cell>
          <cell>2.15</cell>
          <cell>2.21</cell>
          <cell>2.12</cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell>2.19</cell>
          <cell>2.27</cell>
          <cell>2.14</cell>
          <cell>2.20</cell>
          <cell>2.16</cell>
          <cell>2.23</cell>
        </row>
      </tabular>
    </table>
    <p>
      At the <m>0.05</m> significance level, test whether the current mean
      dissolved carbon dioxide concentration differs from 2.10 millimoles per liter.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution><title> Hypotheses</title> 
    <p>
      This is a one-sample <m>t</m>-test for a population mean.
    </p>
    <p>
      Let <m>\mu</m> be the true mean dissolved carbon dioxide concentration.
      The hypotheses are
      <m>H_0:\mu=2.10</m>
      and
      <m>H_a:\mu \ne 2.10</m>.
    </p>
  </solution>
  <solution> <title> Statistical Test</title>
    <p>
      For the sample, the sample size is <m>n=12</m>, the sample mean is
      <m>\bar{x}=2.1817</m>, and the sample standard deviation is
      <m>s\approx 0.0549</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      The test statistic is
      <md>
        t=\frac{\bar{x}-\mu_0}{s/\sqrt{n}}
        =\frac{2.1817-2.10}{0.0549/\sqrt{12}}
        \approx 5.16.
      </md>
    </p>
</solution>
  <solution> <title> p-value</title>
    <p>
      The degrees of freedom are <m>df=n-1=11</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      Using a <m>t</m>-distribution with <m>11</m> degrees of freedom, the
      <m>p</m>-value is less than <m>0.001</m>. In StatKey identify Two Tail to get <m>p=2(0.00016)=0.00032</m> 
    </p>
  </solution>
  <solution> <title> Conclusion</title>
    <p>
      Since <m>p \lt 0.05</m>, we reject <m>H_0</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      There is sufficient evidence at the <m>0.05</m> significance level to
      conclude that the current mean dissolved carbon dioxide concentration
      differs from 2.10 millimoles per liter.
    </p>
    <p>
      Because the sample mean is greater than 2.10, the data suggest that
      the current dissolved carbon dioxide concentration is higher than the
      historical mean.
    </p>
  </solution>
</exercise>

  </subsection>

</section>
